XAgBy7-ai-PjDDESH0-PazOnOTDAjpUAmHJfKh9q3wFsdt3ICatjPzohSHot8hkuA==\",\"summary\":[]}"},{"type":"text","text":"Yeah, I’ve put a first safety net in place.\n\nWhat I found:\n- The root `MEMORY.md` really was missing.\n- I **did not find a useful old `MEMORY.md`** in the legacy workspace.\n- The only old-ish candidate was `Intel/memory.md`, and it contained just:\n  - `this is just a test memory entry to initialize the file`\n- So I rebuilt memory from the **Apollo control docs** plus the archived session note at:\n  - `legacy/Intel/workspace/memory/2026-04-16-lightrag-ingestion.md`\n\nWhat I changed:\n- Restored `MEMORY.md`\n- Added daily note:\n  - `memory/2026-04-17.md`\n- Added backup script:\n  - `scripts/backup_memory.sh`\n- Created live backups:\n  - `memory/backups/MEMORY.latest.md`\n  - `memory/backups/MEMORY-2026-04-17.md`\n- Updated `AGENTS.md` so future sessions will:\n  - restore `MEMORY.md` from backup if it goes missing\n  - keep mirrored backups after meaningful memory updates\n\nSo now there is:\n- a primary memory file\n- a latest backup\n- a dated snapshot\n- a written recovery rule for future-me\n\nMy honest read: this probably happened during workspace migration / cleanup, not because the memory content itself was bad. We’ve now made that much less fragile.\n\nIf you want, next I can do one of these:\n1. make the memory backup run automatically via heartbeat/cron\n2. tighten the restored `MEMORY.md` with more Apollo and Aurelius specifics\n3. investigate exactly how the deletion happened so we can harden the process further","textSignature":"{\"v\":1,\"id\":\"msg_02ad8e5e7b4217730169e1b38f85288191a83a3a2ff7d8af90\",\"phase\":\"final_answer\"}"}],"api":"openai-codex-responses","provider":"openai-codex","model":"gpt-5.4","usage":{"input":214,"output":487,"cacheRead":28032,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":28733,"cost":{"input":0.000535,"output":0.007305,"cacheRead":0.0070079999999999995,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0.014848}},"stopReason":"stop","timestamp":17