_JMzg6qkDPWT8iGlIH_BwiMZgtYiZs2uAoSZgZIzZ_P-1QdoX-7cvbnVgvvTGA70De7qsRS2rDzbjXXAUhPhHXfunTE_JvyjnM9sooj6geuMDsnf5dzEDDowc28_dUIcGlgFWXMwm_osP-cAb-qkv4qHHTKPItac_0FnosUpq_7xzQE8ak6YcpzedwD3H2gCRYVOVzb6P0ZnZOdugNLZNLdyzVvQTjEoOIeRVyhrcNW82fLAXwG4tVT6K4EfEyrn53l6X5zPc308elfFc5oTciKVKsl_oFKBZ582d8qmro8xUZpsj1gXJztBsvKMZcR8fIx01j3WRPXMS7fShyqR8zvxHLdbAUCKUifUPYNmC_x06bfBRnYXOxWgxFyXN6FCDGNNmAKhzGpVLles0A0eL1GErBPeuXJh7qJttbsIP4SJDQcC2l7fsVfrzlmnjGCz6FfCsIT8nfeHBArfrkA02DtaPP4w7H5T-Daphf50iz_q5GqI1NJSHl6FtJrKonmPu1wZGbWwfXjUFa4MN7XH5jf8uxCUOmpkqWrEP-l_IL9-yEblGQc8loX9ZoodhbuH1qa4uiNEG17Rt5ZGX4SYBFRuHhPjo4WAtjpEszia3vG-AllxMw06gESzRn2Fs-a0jOvPsCU0Y1HxoCmBYOKTdFol0sCxMxvDR0zdxv2SkMqVQKK024kqxgRbvxNVYOi2pSyQBTkeo0x4PfstB8o090ZymWGmVlY6dXaysPYFkPH_2QcfdKEuEzaM4-uIFnel3DNd2YSC2z2seiJCDM78U4dVYmDaI10wIrp6ZDfixWvOthhpt0k3PPhH-CYJ9kAkS4a6IutDysFLKCT3dSgHPKy--oJ_jhTKwUHdFyWVQWOa0ijPF5dfnAAd7QN2ftyXS2VeiQCmf4tgZgI5W-GSNmcEv6XbDb7bkXduvIWp9BD3NaqUpimSDWA0-qMOLY=\",\"summary\":[{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Inspecting Docker Compose settings**\\n\\nI need to inspect the compose file for missing versions, which might not be necessary. It’s worth mentioning the difference between docker-compose and docker compose on modern Windows. I should focus on standby and restarts, explaining what it means for containers—sometimes they survive sleep, but GPU and network services might not recover. I'll suggest using restart policies and health checks, and perhaps auto-starting Docker Desktop at login. The user asked for an audit file, so I'll document the issues and recommendations, including considerations like `depends_on` without health checks.\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Structuring the audit for security hardening**\\n\\nI need to focus on security hardening and ensure that I have explicit approval before changing any state—an audit is sufficient for now. I might mention that the shutdown script should use `docker compose stop` with a timeout, or possibly `docker compose down`. Since the user wants to address standby and restarts, the shutdown process should only stop stateful services gracefully. I'll structure the audit into key sections, including an overall verdict, docker-compose findings, a bat audit, and recommended hardening steps with line references, avoiding excessive wording.\"}]}"},{"type":"text","text":"Yep. Here’s the tight audit.\n\n## Overall verdict\n\nCurrent setup is **functional but not hardened for standby / reboot recovery**.\n\nBiggest weaknesses:\n1. inconsistent restart behavior\n2. no healthchecks / readiness gating\n3. brittle startup/shutdown scripts\n4. secrets in compose\n5. public port exposure by default\n\n---\n\n## `docker-compose.yaml` audit\n\n### Critical issues\n\n1. **Missing restart policies on key services**\n   - `docling` lines 52-59\n   - `lightrag` lines 62-79\n   - `n8n` lines 99-112\n   - `n8n_db` lines 114-122\n   - `open-webui` lines 125-138\n\nWhy it matters:\n- after Docker restart, host reboot, or some resume events, these may not come back automatically.\n\nRecommendation:\n- add `restart: unless-stopped` to all long-lived services.\n\n---\n\n2. **`depends_on` is startup order, not readiness**\n   - `apollo-agent` depends on `ollama`, lines 47-49\n   - `lightrag` depends on `ollama`, lines 78-79\n   - `n8n` depends on `n8n_db`, lines 111-112\n   - `open-webui` depends on `ollama`, lines 137-138\n\nWhy it matters:\n- container starts do not mean service is ready\n- after reboot/resume, Apollo may race ahead before Ollama or Postgres is actually usable\n\nRecommendation:\n- add healthchecks\n- use `depends_on: condition: service_healthy` where supported\n\n---\n\n3. **No healthchecks anywhere**\nWhy it matters:\n- Docker has no way to tell healthy from merely running\n- standby wake failures often show up as “container alive, service dead”\n\nMinimum healthchecks to add:\n- `ollama`: HTTP probe on 11434\n- `apollo-agent`: HTTP health or TCP probe on 18789\n- `lightrag`: HTTP probe on 9621\n- `n8n_db`: `pg_isready`\n- `n8n`: HTTP probe on 5678\n- `open-webui`: HTTP probe on 8080\n- `docling`: HTTP probe on 5001 if available\n\n---\n\n4. **Secrets are in the compose file**\n   - `POSTGRES_PASSWORD` line 119\n   - `WEBUI_SECRET_KEY` line 132\n\nWhy it matters:\n- bad hygiene\n- easy accidental leak\n- especially risky in a workspace meant for ingestion/retrieval\n\nRecommendation:\n- move all secrets to `.env` or Docker secrets\n- keep compose declarative, not secret-bearing\n\n---\n\n### Important issues\n\n5. **Ports bind on all interfaces**\n   - all `ports:` entries currently expose broadly\n\nWhy it matters:\n- on a Windows workstation this may expose services to LAN or more, depending on Docker/Desktop/network config\n\nRecommendation:\n- if this is meant to be local-first, bind explicitly to localhost:\n  - `127.0.0.1:11434:11434`\n  - `127.0.0.1:18789:18789`\n  - etc.\n- only expose externally if you intentionally need remote access\n\n---\n\n6. **No graceful shutdown tuning**\nWhy it matters:\n- stateful services like Postgres and app services can get cut off too fast on shutdown/restart\n\nRecommendation:\n- add `stop_grace_period`\n- especially for:\n  - `n8n_db`\n  - `n8n`\n  - `apollo-agent`\n  - `open-webui`\n  - `lightrag`\n\n---\n\n7. **No `init: true`**\nWhy it matters:\n- helps reap zombie processes cleanly\n- useful for long-running app containers\n\nRecommendation:\n- add `init: true` to app services, especially:\n  - `apollo-agent`\n  - `open-webui`\n  - `n8n`\n  - `crawl4ai`\n  - `browserless`\n\n---\n\n8. **Image tags are all `latest`**\nWhy it matters:\n- restarts may behave differently after image refreshes\n- reproducibility suffers\n\nRecommendation:\n- pin versions once stable\n\n---\n\n### Lower priority, but worth fixing\n\n9. **Legacy compatibility mounts add path ambiguity**\n   - lines 42-46\n\nWhy it matters:\n- useful short term, messy long term\n- increases path drift risk\n\nRecommendation:\n- keep temporarily, but treat as migration debt\n\n---\n\n10. **No named network / network policy**\nNot fatal, but defining an internal network would make the stack cleaner and easier to reason about.\n\n---\n\n## `apollo_up.bat` audit\n\n### Problems\n\n1. **Deletes lock files bluntly**\n   - line 4\n\nRisk:\n- could mask a real state issue\n- “delete locks and hope” is not elegant recovery\n\n2. **Uses fixed sleep instead of readiness checks**\n   - line 8\n\nRisk:\n- 5 seconds is arbitrary\n- Ollama may still be cold starting\n\n3. **Uses `docker exec -it` in a script**\n   - line 9\n\nRisk:\n- `-it` is interactive/TTY-oriented and brittle in automated flows\n- bad fit for scheduled or non-interactive startup\n\n4. **Always pulls embedding model on startup**\n   - line 9\n\nRisk:\n- slows startup\n- may hang/fail if network is weird\n- should be bootstrap/init behavior, not every boot behavior\n\n5. **No error handling**\n   - lines 7, 9, 12\n\nRisk:\n- script keeps going even if a core step fails\n\n6. **Launches URLs blindly**\n   - lines 15-16\n\nRisk:\n- browser opens before services are ready\n\n### Recommendation\n`apollo_up.bat` should:\n- verify Docker is available\n- start required containers\n- wait for service health, not sleep blindly\n- ensure models only if missing\n- fail fast on critical errors\n- only open browser when services respond\n\n---\n\n## `apollo_down.bat` audit\n\n### Problems\n\n1. **`docker-compose stop` only**\n   - line 4\n\nThis is not terrible, but incomplete.\nIt stops containers, it does not validate clean completion.\n\n2. **No timeout / no health confirmation**\nRisk:\n- Postgres or app services may still be mid-write\n\n3. **`nvidia-smi` is cosmetic**\n   - line 7\n\nIt does not actually “release VRAM” in a meaningful managed way.\nIt only reports status.\n\n4. **Claims all state saved**\n   - line 10\n\nThat statement is stronger than the script actually guarantees.\n\n### Recommendation\n`apollo_down.bat` should:\n- stop services with explicit timeout\n- optionally stop in dependency-aware order\n- confirm containers stopped\n- optionally archive/log state snapshot\n- print truthful status, not optimistic theater\n\n---\n\n## Best hardening changes, in order\n\n### Priority 1\n1. add `restart: unless-stopped` everywhere appropriate\n2. add healthchecks\n3. add readiness-based startup logic\n4. move inline secrets out of compose\n5. bind ports to `127.0.0.1` unless remote access is intentional\n\n### Priority 2\n6. add `stop_grace_period`\n7. add `init: true`\n8. improve `apollo_up.bat` to wait on health instead of `timeout`\n9. improve `apollo_down.bat` to verify clean stop\n\n### Priority 3\n10. pin image versions\n11. reduce legacy path aliases over time\n12. define a cleaner bootstrap/init flow for model pulls\n\n---\n\n## My recommendation\n\nIf you want the system to survive standby/restarts gracefully, the real contract should be:\n\n- **compose handles persistence and restart**\n- **healthchecks handle readiness**\n- **startup script orchestrates recovery, not guesswork**\n- **shutdown script performs graceful stop, not just ceremony**\n\n---\n\n## Blunt verdict by file\n\n- `docker-compose.yaml`: **good prototype, not hardened**\n- `apollo_up.bat`: **useful rough bootstrap, too brittle**\n- `apollo_down.bat`: **safe-ish convenience wrapper, not a real shutdown routine**\n\n---\n\nIf you want, next I can do one of these:\n\n1. **patch `docker-compose.yaml` for hardening**\n2. **rewrite `apollo_up.bat` and `apollo_down.bat` cleanly**\n3. **do both in one pass**\n\nI’d recommend **3**.","textSignature":"{\"v\":1,\"id\":\"msg_02ad8e5e7b4217730169e1bb1af1f08191bcb54f816e63b6a7\",\"phase\":\"final_answer\"}"}],"api":"openai-codex-responses","provider":"openai-codex","model":"gpt-5.4","usage":{"input":2134,"output":2147,"cacheRead":75904,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":80185,"cost":{"input":0.005335,"output":0.032205,"cacheRead":0.018976,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0.056516}},"stopReason":"stop","time