{"type":"message","id":"b3bcd020","parentId":"c5743d90","timestamp":"2026-04-17T06:32:46.519Z","message":{"role":"toolResult","toolCallId":"call_VnWu0p3dMCkX7kughkX4DWeZ|fc_02ad8e5e7b4217730169e1d40e387881918f715a0d1262e03e","toolName":"memory_search","content":[{"type":"text","text":"{\n  \"results\": [\n    {\n      \"id\": \"0433e5150aa692ad6d963eabfb38a7b12a381eb46294e009bcac7d3743484eb6\",\n      \"path\": \"memory/2026-04-17.md\",\n      \"startLine\": 1,\n      \"endLine\": 12,\n      \"score\": 0.7324877206765661,\n      \"textScore\": 0.7324877206765661,\n      \"snippet\": \"# 2026-04-17\\n\\n- The root `MEMORY.md` was discovered missing after the session history was lost when the PC went into standby.\\n- Searched for old memory copies. `Intel/memory.md` exists but only contained a test line, so it was not useful as a real recovery source.\\n- Recovered Apollo continuity from `projects/apollo/` control docs and from the archived session note `legacy/Intel/workspace/memory/2026-04-16-lightrag-ingestion.md`.\\n- Rebuilt a fresh root `MEMORY.md` with the durable Apollo context and continuity rules.\\n- Added a `memory/backups/` backup path and a simple backup script so future `MEMORY.md` changes can be mirrored.\\n- Updated `AGENTS.md` with instructions to restore `MEMORY.md` f\\n\\nSource: memory/2026-04-17.md#L1-L12\",\n      \"source\": \"memory\",\n      \"citation\": \"memory/2026-04-17.md#L1-L12\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"3184d4e207958fa376dcd655acf6604669004e9146cd8b7247b02eafba0005c2\",\n      \"path\": \"memory/backups/MEMORY-2026-04-17.md\",\n      \"startLine\": 35,\n      \"endLine\": 44,\n      \"score\": 0.34938711681559326,\n      \"textScore\": 0.34938711681559326,\n      \"snippet\": \"- Prefer staged, practical progress over architecture sprawl.\\n- Reuse existing stack and cleaned corpus before building more automation.\\n- Do not ingest secrets or irrelevant runtime debris casually.\\n- Preserve explicit project boundaries: Apollo, Aurelius, Shared, Other.\\n\\n## Memory durability rule\\n- `MEMORY.md` matters and should not silently disappear.\\n- If `MEMORY.md` is ever missing in a main session, restore it from `memory/backups/MEMORY.latest.md` if available, otherwise reconstruct it from recent daily notes and canonical project files, then tell the user.\\n- After meaningful edits to `MEMORY.md`, keep a mirrored backup in `memory/backups/`.\\n\\nSource: memory/backups/MEMORY-2026-04-17.md#L35-L44\",\n      \"source\": \"memory\",\n      \"citation\": \"memory/backups/MEMORY-2026-04-17.md#L35-L44\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"84c52d2036f86e6e1d177d1ffb8ad2fcf87988455738434ce80652fdd818dc21\",\n      \"path\": \"memory/backups/MEMORY.latest.md\",\n      \"startLine\": 35,\n      \"endLine\": 44,\n      \"score\": 0.34938711681559326,\n      \"textScore\": 0.34938711681559326,\n      \"snippet\": \"- Prefer staged, practical progress over architecture sprawl.\\n- Reuse existing stack and cleaned corpus before building more automation.\\n- Do not ingest secrets or irrelevant runtime debris casually.\\n- Preserve explicit project boundaries: Apollo, Aurelius, Shared, Other.\\n\\n## Memory durability rule\\n- `MEMORY.md` matters and should not silently disappear.\\n- If `MEMORY.md` is ever missing in a main session, restore it from `memory/backups/MEMORY.latest.md` if available, otherwise reconstruct it from recent daily notes and canonical project files, then tell the user.\\n- After meaningful edits to `MEMORY.md`, keep a mirrored backup in `memory/backups/`.\\n\\nSource: memory/backups/MEMORY.latest.md#L35-L44\",\n      \"source\": \"memory\",\n      \"citation\": \"memory/backups/MEMORY.latest.md#L35-L44\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"3f6075d286184b913f5a4b1347fcd9dcef5d7e3013abf4144f5e1e91109d3f29\",\n      \"path\": \"MEMORY.md\",\n      \"startLine\": 37,\n      \"endLine\": 45,\n      \"score\": 0.3409816424653573,\n      \"textScore\": 0.3409816424653573,\n      \"snippet\": \"- D