OwwrcPsaDnarj9rCs20u-N-aNSy\",\"summary\":[{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Considering lock file management**\\n\\nI'm thinking about handling stale lock files, but I don't want to edit files unnecessarily. Maybe I should instead archive these locks to a backup folder with a timestamp? The idea of deleting lock files is questionable since I want the startup process to be robust. Perhaps I could remove certain locks only if there are no active containers running, but maybe it's best to avoid deletion entirely unless it’s a known issue.\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Evaluating system startup**\\n\\nI want to avoid deleting any locks, but I could add an optional backup feature for locks in the `legacy\\\\Backups\\\\locks\\\\` folder before starting up. If services start without issues, that might be unnecessary though. I should handle pulling the embedding model only if it’s missing, maybe by executing a command to check for it. It’s also worth ensuring the `Apollo-Architect` model is in place. I’ll need to start `ollama` first and monitor for health before proceeding with other services.\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Designing a shutdown script**\\n\\nI’m thinking about the best way to stop services gracefully, especially since it’s likely running on PC and not headless. I need a script that detects the compose command and uses `docker compose stop -t 45`. I’ll consider stopping the app services in order like `open-webui`, `n8n`, and others before the database, maybe `n8n_db`. To ensure everything stops smoothly, I should verify containers are stopped using commands to check their status. This way, I know nothing is still running.\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Organizing Docker setup**\\n\\nI’m thinking about starting with only ollama to ensure health checks on the embedded model, then running `compose up -d`. I want to ensure the health of key services afterward. I might need to set specific container names like ollama, apollo-agent, and a few others. It could be useful to have a `docker-compose` fallback too. I need to detect the working directory and possibly backup current bat files before making edits. I might log to `legacy\\\\Backups\\\\logs`, but I’m not sure it’s necessary.\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Updating project documentation**\\n\\nI’m considering crafting new content and updating project documentation, especially since there's been meaningful progress with Apollo. I think it’s important to at least update the status, checklist, and decisions in status.json, as it seems significant. We’ve already noted that the next step is rewriting bat files in the docs, so I should definitely update those afterward. Also, I want to remember to update my daily notes, since the phrase \\\"remember this\\\" feels meaningful!\"}]}"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_TKqTLrHSw7M9GYGlEhJQCOin|fc_02ad8e5e7b4217730169e1d9d082ac8191ba4a2711c8789519","name":"update_plan","arguments":{"plan":[{"step":"Back up the core files again before editing the batch scripts","status":"in_progress"},{"step":"Rewrite apollo_up.bat with compose detection, health-based waits, and safer model bootstrap","status":"pending"},{"step":"Rewrite apollo_down.bat with graceful ordered shutdown and verification","status":"pending"},{"step":"Update Apollo continuity docs to record the batch script hardening","status":"pending"}]},"partialJson":"{\"plan\":[{\"step\":\"Back up the core files again before editing the batch scripts\",\"status\":\"in_progress\"},{\"step\":\"Rewrite apollo_up.bat with compose detection, health-based waits, and safer model bootstrap\",\"status\":\"pending\"},{\"step\":\"Rewrite apollo_down.bat with graceful ordered shutdown and verification\",\"status\":\"pending\"},{\"step\":\"Update Apollo continuity docs to record the batch script hardening\",\"status\":\"pending\"}]}"}],"api":"openai-codex-responses","provider":"openai-codex","model":"gpt-5.4","usage":{"input":11875,"output":1