{"type":"message","id":"e63b428c","parentId":"f4443bce","timestamp":"2026-04-17T06:57:25.532Z","message":{"role":"toolResult","toolCallId":"call_rqEiWm0fbjq5MsxIXUkqJQY3|fc_02ad8e5e7b4217730169e1d9d5b658819198b3f8cc1a678144","toolName":"read","content":[{"type":"text","text":"@echo off\r\nTITLE Apollo Station - Ignition\r\necho [1/4] Clearing stale AI locks...\r\nif exist \"Intel\\*.lock\" del /q \"Intel\\*.lock\"\r\n\r\necho [2/4] Starting Ollama and Pulling Embeddings...\r\ndocker-compose up -d ollama\r\ntimeout /t 5\r\ndocker exec -it ollama ollama pull nomic-embed-text\r\n\r\necho [3/4] Starting Full Station Orchestration...\r\ndocker-compose up -d --remove-orphans\r\n\r\necho [4/4] Launching Sovereign Interfaces...\r\nstart http://localhost:18789\r\nstart http://localhost:3000\r\n\r\necho ==========================================\r\necho STATION ONLINE - RESEARCH COMMENCING\r\necho ==========================================\r\ntimeout /t 5"}],"isError":false,"timestamp":1776409045524}}
{"type":"message","id":"25a8b3bc","parentId":"e63b428c","timestamp":"2026-04-17T06:57:25.539Z","message":{"role":"toolResult","toolCallId":"call_AkEP6tPvUxP3frLuVSk1AA8z|fc_02ad8e5e7b4217730169e1d9d5b66881919acc47d38dbe1f59","toolName":"read","content":[{"type":"text","text":"@echo off\r\nTITLE Apollo Station - Safe Shutdown\r\necho [1/2] Gracefully parking the Council...\r\ndocker-compose stop\r\n\r\necho [2/2] Releasing 5070 Ti VRAM...\r\nnvidia-smi\r\n\r\necho ==========================================\r\necho STATION HIBERNATING - ALL STATE SAVED\r\necho ==========================================\r\ntimeout /t 3"}],"isError":false,"timestamp":1776409045532}}
{"type":"message","id":"23dd22a0","parentId":"25a8b3bc","timestamp":"2026-04-17T06:58:19.281Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"**Considering file writing syntax**\n\nI need to write new files, and it's important to ensure I use robust batch syntax. I wonder what the best practices are for this. Should I check examples of batch files or look for specific commands that are commonly used? It seems like I have to pay attention to the syntax rules to avoid errors. I'll gather resources and make sure everything works as expected!\n\n**Drafting batch script for Apollo**\n\nI’m working on drafting the `apollo_up.bat` file. I need to ensure the syntax is correct to enable extensions and delayed expansion, as well as navigate to the right directory. I’m setting up several stack services such as Ollama and others. I also need to incorporate checks for Docker and Compose, as well as verify the Docker daemon is reachable. Each step will check readiness for components and ensure everything is running smoothly. I'll be careful with my commands to avoid errors!\n\n**Organizing container setup**\n\nI might use health checks for all containers. The lightrag service has the container name `apollo-lightrag`, but when using `compose up`, it just uses `lightrag`. I realize `docling` is simply `docling`, and `crawl4ai` is `apollo-scout`. n8n_db has health checks too. I think I need to order health checks, waiting on n8n_db before starting n8n since `depends_on` is currently set to check for service readiness. I could have the up script wait for healthy n8n_db first.\n\n**Refining shutdown script**\n\nI need to address the service names versus container names. For stopping the services, I’ll use the service names from the YAML: `lightrag`, `crawl4ai`, `browserless`, `ollama`, `apollo-agent`, `n8n_db`, and `open-webui`. It seems like verifying with container names could be easier since they’re more explicit. I might also want to ensure that the stop order includes the `apollo-lightrag` service as `lightrag`. Additionally, I could use `docker inspect` to check if the containers are not running. If that fails due to the container not existing, I'll count it as okay.\n\n**Evaluating scripting options**\n\nI’m considering the potential need for warnings in case a container isn’t found. I wonder if I might encounter errors with certain commands if some services aren’t created, but I think it’s unlikely. I should simplify things by using a straightforward script instead of PowerShell. It might make sense to run `docker compose up -d n8n_db ollama` early since n8n_db isn’t needed until the full stack. I’ll need to ensure that `.lock` files aren’t deleted and check local URLs, but that might be overkill.","thinkingSignature":"{\"id\":\"rs_02ad8e5e7b4217730169e1d9d7bf6481919d765a295fc75142\",\"type\":\"reasoning\",\"encrypted_content\":\"gAAAAABp4dn5n4rmK0LCMi5SgT6Wd6oif7uDU46EFUJfSWtXiCAXoOlQrvsMALeWaqbYiG354qsWHcUrawruL7QUGHo6OWjwImJXc9GUJHnS2G0O-7Gg1q-07ErkYbXdiH2EuD1JBMk-PXA376wqRAIIuVh-43h-wXCl1gWwA5CY66OUBlGQf646kHkuySdQ6UNbkkueHAMpRYnq_dhhp5w67QbIJYO71RK6nBPxYusBXqDSf1ZLdgsU1vfMoMAPp0z8J_RVFc_k1Bmv0rUZuUCIQ6lbFlQ5sQ5TYnviSoLBOEBVoGJDIGj59nvB5lUQO9aF3tSLDNmmF7tLgseAgr466uVowpFzS4dTT3nm9wnoAzQMmBEIeFfqLthA1mYqkUNNA6Bs433JPCtlcxA1L3mrfIIO7dE_TmXK5haJnFFLakAdAn6bdv4HJrr8t3pLGwsmJfQngZd-fwR2QA845V6PFAjrR8-VB7ugmGzBvNFB1lRnE96viOr8xay3G9HS_xFwUMkc0h5Zj8a5x4-kNqgyONWNl9yj_tic0tyI4cTkDoWtah29O4N_RTpttjY0-EYnwu7Ms57iu2aV4CnimKJgD2sZB_ut4gbmrt4Odz5T7puc9M_rcvBZk6xeY-R1vAtKswpGo9fXJHzolf2jPEof8HNrIgQokwNuLLpuS92gPTLBrVwMSeq-JufbfQVUYufa356oIOGxxIMdh1xXzeSNaV-xUvvJKX_Rm2HajPfBrWd_rouh1WaLyNjhA-uLIs1zGet4l3owtTKdsljR1pTvE9xjSrVoEkP1shnERDFiHw41GhGinB5lAZipps_9zbnUtIE_UIZlcyBeg-nTU9x5eNycmVOHGfrJfif6cMkgA0HI_FqYZTdzf6EGHNo_2Yk71JykUrppEXElvKQDLRBk2rsa4Vilhy3LumjXp-K1xABjIamX-yOCSkG_NIxgIMmq7r3VTJp1DcgSFgzfC8KsuE9pgKNJ8YUynJcRa2e56BSxdII0_21BtiPhguBygVGhaGHxnNMsmZLdNUzJOsSVs03G27aD3rnSszgxqlnKj_6OClQj9WyH_XqyCkjS5r9XI1VCMpcBn0Mt