KXfnzGCfO80usEvBQSu2FJ28XLLfH_Ba7moJRwkj2DP\",\"summary\":[]}"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_W4jNBn6peXxJxs09iYsEpxmY|fc_02ad8e5e7b4217730169e1e9e51bf08191b78f6aea1a8434d0","name":"write","arguments":{"path":"memory/2026-04-17.md","content":"# 2026-04-17\n\n- The root `MEMORY.md` was discovered missing after the session history was lost when the PC went into standby.\n- Searched for old memory copies. `Intel/memory.md` exists but only contained a test line, so it was not useful as a real recovery source.\n- Recovered Apollo continuity from `projects/apollo/` control docs and from the archived session note `legacy/Intel/workspace/memory/2026-04-16-lightrag-ingestion.md`.\n- Rebuilt a fresh root `MEMORY.md` with the durable Apollo context and continuity rules.\n- Added a `memory/backups/` backup path and a simple backup script so future `MEMORY.md` changes can be mirrored.\n- Updated `AGENTS.md` with instructions to restore `MEMORY.md` from backup if it ever goes missing again.\n- Added a local `scripts/memory_backup_daemon.sh` watchdog and started it with a 10-minute interval so `MEMORY.md` is backed up automatically.\n- The user added a new workspace rule: before modifying core project/runtime files like `docker-compose.yaml`, `apollo_up.bat`, `apollo_down.bat`, `.env`, and similar files, create dated/versioned backups in `legacy/Backups/`.\n- Seeded `legacy/Backups/` with backups of `docker-compose.yaml`, `apollo_up.bat`, `apollo_down.bat`, `.env`, and `AGENTS.md`, and added `scripts/backup_core_project_files.sh` to make that easier to follow consistently.\n- Backed up `docker-compose.yaml` and `.env` again as `v2` snapshots before hardening them.\n- Hardened `docker-compose.yaml` with restart policies, `init: true`, graceful stop periods, and core service healthchecks, while keeping remote-access port exposure unchanged.\n- Moved compose-managed secrets into `.env` and added `POSTGRES_PASSWORD`, `WEBUI_SECRET_KEY`, and the existing `N8N_ENCRYPTION_KEY` there.\n- Deliberately did **not** switch `n8n` to Postgres in this pass, to avoid silently stranding the existing SQLite-backed state.\n- Updated Apollo control docs to record the hardening decisions and next validation steps.\n- Backed up the core project files again as `v3` snapshots before rewriting `apollo_up.bat` and `apollo_down.bat`.\n- Rewrote `apollo_up.bat` to detect Docker/Compose, wait for health instead of sleeping blindly, and only pull `nomic-embed-text` if it is missing.\n- Rewrote `apollo_down.bat` to do ordered shutdown, verify containers are no longer running, and avoid pretending that `nvidia-smi` itself releases VRAM.\n- After restart the full Apollo stack came back healthy (`docker-compose ps` showed all core services healthy), and the `MEMORY.md` backup daemon was restarted successfully.\n- Recovered the previously lost session content into `legacy/Recovered-Sessions/2026-04-17-lost-session-recovery.md`, including the exact recovered \"ok lets proceed to definig contract then\" exchange and the key Apollo decisions recovered from saved session transcripts.\n- The next environment-authority priorities were identified as: working Docker/Compose control from the OpenClaw runtime, proper Git integration, persistent startup for maintenance helpers, and eventually an Apollo-specific skill.\n- A key architectural conclusion was reached: Apollo should likely use a hybrid dual-plane model, where the normal assistant remains inside the Apollo stack but at least one out-of-band control/recovery path exists outside it.\n- That dual-plane architecture question was intentionally pinned for later because the stack is currently functional; the immediate focus returns to Project Apollo itself.\n"},"partialJson":"{\"path\":\"memory/2026-04-17.md\",\"content\":\"# 2026-04-17\\n\\n- The root `MEMORY.md` was discovered missing after the session history was lost when the PC went into standby.\\n- Searched for old memory copies. `Intel/memory.md` exists but only contained a test line, so it was not useful as a real recovery source.\\n- Recovered Apollo continuity from `projects/apollo/` control docs and from the archived session note `legacy/Intel/workspace/memory/2026-04-16-lightrag-ingestion.md`.\\n- Rebuilt a fresh root `MEMORY.md` with the durable Apollo context and continuity rules.\\n- Added a `memory/backups/` backup path and a simple backup script so future `MEMORY.md` changes can be mirrored.\\n- Updated `AGENTS.md` with instructions to restore `MEMORY.md` from backup if it ever goes missing again.\\n- Added a local `scripts/memory_backup_daemon.sh` watchdog and started it with a 10-minute interval so `MEMORY.md` is backed up automatically.\\n- The user added a new workspace rule: before modifying core project/runtime files like `docker-compose.yaml`, `apollo_up.bat`, `apollo_down.bat`, `.env`, and similar files, create dated/versioned backups in `legacy/Backups/`.\\n- Seeded `legacy/Backups/` with backups of `docker-compose.yaml`, `apollo_up.bat`, `apollo_down.bat`, `.env`, and `AGENTS.md`, and added `scripts/backup_core_project_files.sh` to make that easier to follow consistently.\\n- Backed up `docker-compose.yaml` and `.env` again as `v2` snapshots before hardening them.\\n- Hardened `docker-compose.yaml` with restart policies, `init: true`, graceful stop periods, and core service healthchecks, while keeping remote-access port exposure unchanged.\\n- Moved compose-managed secrets into `.env` and added `POSTGRES_PASSWORD`, `WEBUI_SECRET_KEY`, and the existing `N8N_ENCRYPTION_KEY` there.\\n- Deliberately did **not** switch `n8n` to Postgres in this pass, to avoid silently stranding the existing SQLite-backed state.\\n- Updated Apollo control docs to record the hardening decisions and next validation steps.\\n- Backed up the core project files again as `v3` snapshots before rewriting `apollo_up.bat` and `apollo_down.bat`.\\n- Rewrote `apollo_up.bat` to detect Docker/Compose, wait for health instead of sleeping blindly, and only pull `nomic-embed-text` if it is missing.\\n- Rewrote `apollo_down.bat` to do ordered shutdown, verify containers are no longer running, and avoid pretending that `nvidia-smi` itself releases VRAM.\\n- After restart the full Apollo stack came back healthy (`docker-compose ps` showed all core services healthy), and the `MEMORY.md` backup daemon was restarted successfully.\\n- Recovered the previously lost session content into `legacy/Recovered-Sessions/2026-04-17-lost-session-recovery.md`, including the exact recovered \\\"ok lets proceed to definig contract then\\\" exchange and the key Apollo decisions recovered from saved session transcripts.\\n- The next environment-authority priorities were identified as: working Docker/Compose control from the OpenClaw runtime, proper Git integration, persistent startup for maintenance helpers, and eventually an Apollo-specific skill.\\n- A key architectural conclusion was reached: Apollo should likely use a hybrid dual-plane model, where the normal assistant remains inside the Apollo stack but at least one out-of-band control/recovery path exists outside it.\\n- That dual-plane architecture question was intentionally pinned for later because the stack is currently functional; the immediate focus returns to Project Apollo itself.\\n\"}"}],"api":"openai-codex-responses","provider":"openai-codex","model":"gpt-5.4","usage":{"input":863,"output":935,"cacheRead":96896,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":98694,"cost":{"input":0.0021575,"output":0.014025000000000001,"cacheRead":0.024224,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0.0404065}},"stopReason":"toolUse","timestamp":1776413153171,"responseId":"resp_02ad8e5e7b4217730169e1e9e18b5c8191842d24845db73ea7"}}
